Kumho, Filinvest, MediaTek, Sinopec, Tencent: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-03-16T21:08:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-16/kumho-filinvest-mediatek-sinopec-tencent-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.    China Petroleum & Chemical Corp. (600028)  (386 HK): The nation’s
biggest oil refiner and Kuwait Petroleum Corp. received approval
from  China ’s top economic planning body to build a refinery
project in Guangdong, according to a statement on the National
Development and Reform Commission’s website. The project
consists of a 15 million ton-a-year oil refinery and a 1 million
ton-a-year ethylene plant, the statement said. Sinopec, as the
company is also known, rose 0.1 percent to HK$7.77.    Filinvest Land Inc. (FLI)  : The Philippine developer’s
2010 net income jumped 46 percent to 2.95 billion pesos ($67.4
million) from 2.02 billion pesos a year earlier, it said in an
e-mailed statement in  Manila . The amount includes a one-time
gain of 526 million pesos, Filinvest said. Revenue last year
rose 45 percent to 8.25 billion pesos. The company said last
year’s profit was a record. The stock climbed 2.8 percent to
1.11 pesos.    Hana Financial Group Inc. (086790)  (086790 KS): The company’s
banking unit, Hana Bank, raised 10 billion won ($8.8 million)
selling three-year bonds to repay debt, according to a
regulatory filing. Hana Financial,  South Korea ’s fourth-largest
financial company, advanced 4.8 percent to 44,000 won.  Kumho Tire Co. (073240 KS): South Korea’s second-largest
tire maker plans to send a team to China today to investigate
whether workers at its Tianjin factory failed to follow its
regulations on the use of recycled rubber, the company said in
an e-mailed response. Most tire makers use a certain amount of
recycled rubber in the manufacturing of new tires, according to
the statement. Kumho Tire rose 0.7 percent to 15,300 won.    MediaTek Inc. (2454)  (2454 TT): Taiwan’s largest chip designer
will buy all of  Ralink Technology Corp. (3534)  (3534 TT) in a share
swap, Ralink Chief Executive Officer Fang Shin-jou said.
MediaTek rose 3.1 percent to NT$328.50, while Ralink jumped 6.9
percent to NT$103.50.  Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. (2330 TT): The
world’s largest contract chipmaker bought NT$2.37 billion ($80.2
million) of equipment from two suppliers, Hsinchu-based TSMC
said in two separate statements to the Taiwan stock exchange. It
purchased NT$1.87 billion of gear from ASML Hong Kong Ltd. and
NT$507 million from ASML Taiwan Ltd., the chipmaker said. The
stock climbed 0.7 percent to NT$68.50.    Tencent Holdings Ltd. (700)  (700 HK): China’s biggest Internet
company posted fourth-quarter net income of 2.2 billion yuan
($334.7 million), according to a statement to the Hong Kong
stock exchange. That compares with the 2.24 billion yuan average
estimate of nine analysts in a survey compiled by Bloomberg.
Tencent gained 1.3 percent to HK$216.80.  To contact the reporter on this story:
